{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493214"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:00:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:00:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1256"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1256"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.19,0.01,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1256"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103645"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1256"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1256"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86062"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"679"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7696"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103645"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of sudden onset of severe pain in his left leg. His medical history includes atrial fibrillation, for which he takes apixaban. On examination his blood pressure is 142/84 mmHg and an irregular pulse 100/min. The left leg is pale, cool and no pulses can be felt below the femoral pulse. He is complaining of paraesthesia on the dorsum of the foot and is showing signs of reduced foot dorsiflexion. A CT angiogram is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to anticoagulation, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Embolectomy +/- catheter directed thrombolysis","Balloon angioplasty +/- stent insertion","Non operative management","Femoro-popliteal bypass","Atherectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient gives a picture of acute limb ischaemia because of the presence of severe pain of acute onset, paraesthesia, and reduced dorsiflexion of the foot with a pale, cool leg and no pulses below the femoral pulse. This indicates the presence of blood flow obstruction which is most probably due to an embolus secondary to atrial fibrillation. It is further confirmed by the presence of an embolus obstructing the proximal popliteal artery seen in the CT angiogram.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERutherford\u0027s classification is used to classify acute limb ischaemia and according to that, the patient belongs to the IIb category. A picture is attached below explaining different stages (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmbolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the procedure of choice in patients with this category of acute limb ischaemia. It will help in rapidly resolving the symptoms by manually removing the source of obstruction i.e the embolus. On-table catheter directed lysis may also be used as an adjunct during embolectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBalloon angioplasty +/- Stent insertion \u003C/strong\u003Eis an endovascular procedure that can help the patient in alleviating the disease but it is used together with an embolectomy procedure, it is not used alone because even though it will help in increasing the size of the lumen, it will not remove the source of obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon operative management \u003C/strong\u003Eis not a valid option in this patient as the symptoms are limb threatening. Anticoagulation alone may be used in patients with Rutherford 1 symptoms that have remained stable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoro-popliteal bypass\u003C/strong\u003E is a more advanced procedure and it involves creating an alternate route for the blood to go around the obstruction, it is an option if embolectomy has failed to relieve the obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtherectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate in patients in whom the main source of obstruction is an atheroma, patients with elevated lipid levels and elevated HbA1c. These would be patients with a history of myocardial infarction/ischaemic stroke, etc. In this patient, the main source of obstruction is an embolus arising from the heart secondary to atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Embolectomy is the procedure of choice in patients with severe acute limb ischaemia."],"references":["Creager M A, Kaufman J A, Conte M S. Clinical practice. Acute limb ischemia. N Engl J Med. 2012;366(23):2198\u20132206."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86062"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1256"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18529"},{"type":"media","id":"18530"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18531"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18529"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/233a7ead-1abb-4e37-9e06-b378a7c94868.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/233a7ead-1abb-4e37-9e06-b378a7c94868.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":377,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"18530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18530"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/91538882-d3f0-4bea-a26f-4e759a4f3c4c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://a